Got it! Let's adapt the rules for your project. Given your requirements and the simplicity often needed in game development, I recommend using `dig` for dependency injection. Also, we'll update the project structure to reflect modern Go practices.

### Updated Project Rules

# Core Project Rules
- Always use the project's import path `github.com/jonesrussell/gimbal`
- Always implement proper interface abstractions following Go best practices
- Use `dig` for dependency injection

# Dependency Injection & Application Structure
- Integrate `dig` for dependency injection:
  - Initialize DI container in `main.go`
  - Use DI modules for organizing dependencies
  - Handle errors appropriately
  - Ensure proper logger initialization before other dependencies

# Core Dependencies
Always use:
- `github.com/hajimehoshi/ebiten/v2` for game development
- `go.uber.org/zap` for structured logging

# Concurrency & Safety
- Always use `sync.RWMutex` for concurrent operations in shared data structures
- Always use `context.Context` for cancellation and timeouts
- Never skip error handling
- Never use `init()` functions except for DI module registration

# Code Organization
Files named `types.go` should only contain interface and type definitions

# Component Separation
The separation of concerns is now:
- `core/types.go`: Interface and type definitions
- `core/game.go`: Main game loop and logic
- `core/input.go`: Input handling
- `core/render.go`: Rendering logic
- `assets/`: Game assets like images, sounds, etc.
- `systems/`: Game systems like physics, AI, etc.

# Main Structure
- `main.go`: Main application setup and DI integration
- `config/`: Configuration and settings management
- `cmd/`: Command-line tools and utilities (if needed)

# Testing & Quality
- Run code through `golangci-lint` before suggesting changes
- Implement unit tests for all components
- Use `mockery` for interface mocking
- Include integration tests where appropriate

# Documentation
- Include GoDoc comments for exported types and functions
- Maintain `README.md` with current setup instructions
- Document configuration options

# Logging Standards
- Always use structured logging with `zap`
- Include relevant context in log fields
- Use appropriate log levels (debug, info, warn, error)

# Error Handling
- Always implement proper error handling and avoid panics
- Use error wrapping with `fmt.Errorf("context: %w", err)`
- Return errors rather than logging and continuing

# Debug Mode Standards
When debug flag (-v, --verbose) is enabled:
- Show detailed debug logs
- Use development logger configuration
- Include debug level messages
- Show detailed timestamps
- Include caller information
- Display colored log output
- Show full error stack traces
